notes.description: As the Wilmington Police Department’s Cold Case Unit continues a 1978 death investigation, police are asking for the assistance of the public. On April 8, 1978, police were dispatched to a landfill in the 600 block of Terminal Avenue, where they located a deceased male subject. The man, who has not yet been identified, was believed to be approximately 17 to 25 years of age, and could have been at that location for as long as 7 years before he was located. Further investigation revealed that the subject had a severe pelvic deformity that would have caused him to walk with a noticeable limp on his right side that may have required the assistance of crutches or a cane. The victim was found wearing a bleached blue, long-sleeved “Kent-Collection By Arrow” shirt, a pair of bleached Levi’s pants (size 32), and undershorts. The Unit has partnered with Moxxy Forensic Investigations, which believes that the subject likely had African American ancestral ties to Georgetown County, South Carolina, and the State of Delaware. Moxxy also identified surnames that could be related to the subject – including Harris, Ray, Rodgers and Dukes. Police encourage anyone with information about this subject – including his identity and/or cause of death – to contact the WPD Cold Case Unit by calling Investigator Steven Rizzo at (302) 576-3937 or Detective Devon Jones at (302) 576-3631.

clothingAndAccessoriesArticles.description: A bleached blue, long-sleeved shirt which was rolled up around the elbow region. A tag at the back of the neck area says "Kent- Collection By Arrow". A pair of blue bleached pants size 32 show "Made in Hong Kong". Printed jersey undershorts also recovered
No items other than what was found on the body
